<span id="freeTextContainer944572265024353397">This book was recommended reading for the course I am taking through coursera.org. <br/><br/>This is not your mother’s Mark Twain, more than likely, it is nothing that you would have expected of Mark Twain. Twain left thousands of pages of notes at his death, over the years these notes would be published. Publication of this particular set of notes were rejected by his daughter who claimed they distorted her father’s view. Since there are a variety of notes, etc., utilized within the contents of this book</span>
  <span id="freeText944572265024353397" style="display:none">This book was recommended reading for the course I am taking through coursera.org. <br /><br />This is not your mother’s Mark Twain, more than likely, it is nothing that you would have expected of Mark Twain. Twain left thousands of pages of notes at his death, over the years these notes would be published. Publication of this particular set of notes were rejected by his daughter who claimed they distorted her father’s view. Since there are a variety of notes, etc., utilized within the contents of this book; it is my belief that the daughter did not wish for certain sarcasm towards religion which eventually became published.<br /><br />While many may be outraged by ‘Letters,’ I personally thought it was quite funny. Why is it that people cannot see humor in religion, especially since it was a man made concept? Is it that people would rather revel in blind faith than be forced to rethink their concepts? Maybe it is simply that people do not want to laugh at themselves. Well, there is always the little Cat-Tale to linger on. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="944572265024353397" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
